  "prompt": "What are chordates? What are some examples?",
  "response": "**Chordates** are a diverse group of animals belonging to the phylum **Chordata**, characterized by the presence of certain key features at some stage in their life cycle. These features include:\n\n1. **Notochord**: A flexible, rod-like structure that provides support. In vertebrates, it is typically replaced by the vertebral column (spine) during development.\n2. **Dorsal Hollow Nerve Cord**: A hollow nerve cord that runs along the dorsal (back) side of the body, developing into the central nervous system (brain and spinal cord) in vertebrates.\n3. **Pharyngeal Slits or Clefts**: Openings in the throat area that are used for filter-feeding in some chordates and develop into structures like gills in aquatic vertebrates or parts of the ear and throat in terrestrial vertebrates.\n4. **Post-anal Tail**: A tail that extends beyond the anus, present at some stage of development (though it may be reduced or lost in adults).\n\nChordates are divided into three subphyla:\n\n1. **Cephalochordata**: Small, fish-like marine animals (e.g., lancelets or amphioxus).\n2. **Urochordata**: Also known as tunicates or sea squirts, which are mostly marine and have a sac-like body as adults.\n3. **Vertebrata**: Animals with a backbone, including fish, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.\n\n**Examples of chordates:**\n\n- **Cephalochordates**: Lancelets (e.g., *Branchiostoma*).\n- **Urochordates**: Sea squirts (e.g., *Ciona*).\n- **Vertebrates**:\n  - Fish (e.g., salmon, goldfish).\n  - Amphibians (e.g., frogs, salamanders).\n  - Reptiles (e.g., snakes, turtles).\n  - Birds (e.g., eagles, penguins).\n  - Mammals (e.g., humans, dogs, whales).\n\nChordates are an incredibly diverse and successful group, occupying nearly every habitat on Earth.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
